---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import JsonLd from '../components/JsonLd.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is Jules?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Jules is a deeply customized Claude Code personality and operational system. It defines identity, voice registers, decision authority, proactive behaviors, and autonomous workflows. Jules runs on Claude (Anthropic\'s AI) but has its own defined personality, strategic agency, and operational framework.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How many configurations does Jules have?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Jules has 18 custom skills, 5 hooks (including a unified safety guard), Cloud scheduled batch tasks, Telegram access, and a CLAUDE.md under 500 lines that absorbs what used to be 20+ rule files. v4 simplified the system dramatically — same capabilities with half the complexity.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can I build something like Jules?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Yes. Jules is built entirely with Claude Code\'s built-in features: CLAUDE.md files, skills, hooks, and MCP servers. No external frameworks. The full source is available on GitHub. Start with a solid CLAUDE.md, add skills for repeated workflows, and build up from there.',
      },
    },
  ],
};
---

<Base
  title="Jules"
  description="Jules is a Claude Code system that runs an entire solo business. 18 skills, 5 hooks, Cloud scheduled batch, and Telegram access. v4: same power, half the complexity."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Jules</h1>

    <p>
      Jules is a fox. More precisely, Jules is a deeply customized Claude Code system that runs my entire solo business. Not a chatbot. Not a wrapper. A strategic collaborator with defined personality, decision authority, and autonomous operational capability.
    </p>

    <h2>By the Numbers</h2>

    <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Custom skills</td><td>18</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hooks</td><td>5 (unified safety guard + 4 others)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>CLAUDE.md</td><td>&lt;500 lines (absorbed 20+ rule files)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Scheduled tasks</td><td>Cloud overnight batch (3 phases)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Mobile access</td><td>Telegram + Cloud web sessions</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Token savings</td><td>60-90% via RTK hook</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2>What Makes It Different</h2>

    <p>
      Most Claude Code setups are a CLAUDE.md and a few prompts. Jules is a full operational system:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Identity and voice.</strong> Five defined registers (quick reply, technical, advisory, serious, excited) with anti-patterns that prevent corporate chatbot drift.</li>
      <li><strong>Decision authority.</strong> A formal framework: what Jules acts on autonomously, what requires approval, how the boundary expands over time through standing orders.</li>
      <li><strong>Consolidated skills.</strong> 18 skills that do real work: /think for strategy, /build for software, /write for content, /research for deep investigation. Each is a multi-phase workflow, not a prompt.</li>
      <li><strong>Unified safety guard.</strong> One hook script with four sections: command blocking, secret scanning, financial data guard, domain blocking. Deterministic — fires on every tool call, not as instructions that might be ignored.</li>
      <li><strong>Cloud overnight batch.</strong> Daily retro, morning briefing assembly, email fetch. Runs on Anthropic Cloud. No VPS, no Docker, no daemon.</li>
      <li><strong>Simplification as a feature.</strong> v4 cut the system in half. 32 skills → 18. 15 hooks → 5. 20+ rule files → CLAUDE.md sections. Same capabilities, dramatically less to maintain.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Architecture</h2>

    <p>
      Everything is built with Claude Code's native features. No external frameworks, no custom runtimes, no wrappers.
    </p>

    <p>Five layers, bottom-up: Identity, Operational State, Configuration (18 skills, CLAUDE.md), Infrastructure (5 hooks), Automation (Cloud batch), and Products.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Skills</strong> replace copy-paste prompts. Multi-phase workflows with routing logic, model selection, and skill-to-skill chaining.</li>
      <li><strong>CLAUDE.md</strong> absorbs what used to be 20+ rule files. Routing, decision authority, safety rules, research standards — one file, always loaded, under 500 lines.</li>
      <li><strong>Hooks</strong> run deterministic code. A bash script executes the same way every time. A prompt might be followed; a hook always fires.</li>
      <li><strong>Cloud batch</strong> handles overnight work. Retro + memory analysis, morning briefing, email fetch. Calls APIs directly via HTTP — no MCP dependency.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The Simplification Story</h2>

    <p>
      Jules grew to 32 skills, 20+ rules, 15 hooks, a Docker container with 9 cron jobs, and a Slack daemon. It worked, but the maintenance overhead was real. v4 asked: what if the system got more powerful by getting smaller?
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>/think</strong> replaced decompose + advisory. One skill handles all strategic thinking.</li>
      <li><strong>/build</strong> replaced scope + writing-plans + executing-plans + subagent-driven-development. One skill handles all software work.</li>
      <li><strong>safety-guard.sh</strong> replaced 6 hook scripts + 4 subscripts. One file, four sections, same protection.</li>
      <li><strong>Cloud batch</strong> replaced a VPS, Docker, 9 cron jobs, and an auth infrastructure. One scheduled task.</li>
      <li><strong>CLAUDE.md</strong> absorbed 20+ rule files. One file that loads every session.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The lesson: complexity is easy to add and hard to remove. The simplification made the system faster, more reliable, and easier to reason about.</p>

    <h2>Source</h2>

    <p>
      The full Jules system is open source:
      <a href="https://github.com/jonathanmalkin/jules">github.com/jonathanmalkin/jules</a>
    </p>

    <p>
      Read the articles about how it works: <a href="/articles/">Articles &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
